<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-142-250  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 142 250.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Jan 1990 v7 n1 p38(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>LAN E-mail: the promise of the '90's.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Courtot, Philippe F.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Local area network-based electronic mail systems, with theirgrowing applications for storing and retrieving information, holdthe potential to facilitate a revolution in work group computing.andO;The emerging generation of mail systems establish enterprise-widenetworks with multiple communications and information managementpotentialities.andP;  At an average cost of $50 per user, they can alsointroduce significant savings into business operations.andP;  Thesystems that are emerging also enable software performing otherfunctions to access the message storage engine.andP;  In addition, newE-mail systems have established compound document architectures asa fundamental message structure, or envelope.andP;  E-mail is alsobecoming an important applications platform.andP;  The adoption of theX.400 standard will further encourage its development.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic Mail SystemsLocal Area NetworksCost of CommunicationsInformation Storage and RetrievalWork Group ComputingStandardsCompound-Document Architecture.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>